                                            +------------------+</div><p class="mt-5 text-lg text-text-secondary reveal">The architecture follows a data flow from renewable input to electrolysis, monitored storage, tracked transport and decision support dashboards.</p></div></div>

  <div class="slide" data-slide="6"><div class="gradient-mesh"><div class="blob" style="width:330px;height:330px;top:-70px;right:-80px;background:var(--color-accent-3);opacity:.08"></div><div class="blob" style="width:220px;height:220px;bottom:-40px;left:-30px;background:var(--color-accent-2);opacity:.07"></div></div><div class="content"><h2 class="font-display text-5xl mb-6 reveal">Literature highlights</h2><table class="mini reveal"><tbody><tr><th>Area</th><th>Key finding</th><th>Project relevance</th></tr><tr><td>Plant architecture</td><td>Green hydrogen plants may be direct-coupled, grid-connected or islanded.</td><td>Supports flexible academic system design.</td></tr><tr><td>Electrolysis</td><td>PEM electrolyzers are preferred for fast load following in renewable systems.</td><td>Useful for dynamic production estimation.</td></tr><tr><td>Storage</td><td>Compression and storage are essential subsystems in complete hydrogen facilities.</td><td>Motivates tank-level monitoring module.</td></tr><tr><td>Optimization</td><td>Modern systems use EMS, forecasting and cost-emission optimization.</td><td>Justifies dashboard analytics and alerts.</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid systems</td><td>PV-wind-hydrogen combinations improve reliability in off-grid and grid-connected cases.</td><td>Supports renewable input module.</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>

  <div class="slide" data-slide="7"><div class="gradient-mesh"><div class="blob" style="width:350px;height:350px;top:-90px;right:-50px;background:var(--color-accent-1);opacity:.08"></div><div class="blob" style="width:250px;height:250px;bottom:-30px;left:-30px;background:var(--color-accent-3);opacity:.06"></div></div><div class="content"><h2 class="font-display text-5xl mb-6 reveal">Existing system problems</h2><div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-6"><div class="bg-glass-bg backdrop-blur-xl border border-glass-border rounded-2xl p-6 reveal"><h3 class="font-bold text-2xl mb-3">Manual practices</h3><ul class="text-text-secondary mini tight pl-5"><li>Separate logs for energy, production and storage.</li><li>Delayed updates from field operators.</li><li>No unified visibility for dispatch planning.</li><li>Report preparation is time-consuming.</li></ul></div><div class="bg-glass-bg backdrop-blur-xl border border-glass-border rounded-2xl p-6 reveal"><h3 class="font-bold text-2xl mb-3">Technical limitations</h3><ul class="text-text-secondary mini tight pl-5"><li>Hard to estimate hydrogen from varying renewable supply.</li><li>Poor alerting for tank capacity and transport delays.</li><li>Data inconsistency across users and departments.</li><li>Weak audit trail and decision support.</li></ul></div></div></div></div>

